      "question": "What are the differences between lists, tuples, sets, and dictionaries in Python? When would you use each?",
      "answer": "<p>Python has four core built-in container types, each with different mutability, ordering, and lookup characteristics. Choosing the right one has a real impact on performance and correctness.</p>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Feature</th><th>List</th><th>Tuple</th><th>Set</th><th>Dictionary</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Syntax</td><td><code>[1, 2, 3]</code></td><td><code>(1, 2, 3)</code></td><td><code>{1, 2, 3}</code></td><td><code>{'a': 1, 'b': 2}</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Mutable</td><td>Yes</td><td>No (immutable)</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Ordered</td><td>Yes (since 3.7)</td><td>Yes</td><td>No*</td><td>Yes (since 3.7)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Duplicates</td><td>Yes</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td><td>Keys: no / Values: yes</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Indexable</td><td>By position</td><td>By position</td><td>No</td><td>By key</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Lookup</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(n)</td><td>O(1)</td><td>O(1)</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Use when</td><td>Order matters, items change</td><td>Fixed record, dict key</td><td>Uniqueness, membership</td><td>Key-value mapping</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p>*Set order is implementation-dependent in CPython.</p>\n<pre><code># Set for fast membership\nblocked = {101, 204, 333}\nif user_id in blocked: ...       # O(1)\n\n# Tuple as dict key\ngrid = {(0, 0): 'origin', (1, 2): 'point'}\n\n# Dict for counting\nfrom collections import Counter\ncounts = Counter(words)\n\n# Tuple for multiple returns\ndef min_max(vals):\n    return min(vals), max(vals)  # unpack: lo, hi = ...\n</code></pre>",
