      "question": "Explain list slicing in Python with step values. What does <code>my_list[::-1]</code> do?",
      "answer": "<p><b>Syntax:</b> <code>seq[start:stop:step]</code>. Start defaults to 0, stop to <code>len(seq)</code>, step to 1. <b>Stop is exclusive</b>. Negative indices count from the end.</p>\n<pre><code>nums = [0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5]\nnums[2:5]       # [2, 3, 4]\nnums[:3]        # [0, 1, 2]        — first 3\nnums[3:]        # [3, 4, 5]        — from index 3\nnums[::2]       # [0, 2, 4]        — every 2nd\nnums[::-1]      # [5, 4, 3, 2, 1, 0] — reversed\n\n# Negative indexing\nnums[-1]        # 5  — last element\nnums[-3:]       # [3, 4, 5] — last 3\n\n# Step > 1 for skipping\ntext = 'abcdefghij'\ntext[1::2]      # 'bdfhj' — odd positions\n\n# Slice assignment (in-place replacement)\nnums[1:3] = [10, 20]  # [0, 10, 20, 3, 4, 5]\n\n# Deleting with slice\ndel nums[2:4]\n</code></pre>\n<p><b>Interview notes:</b> Slicing never raises <code>IndexError</code> — out-of-bounds indices are silently clamped. Slice objects are used internally: <code>slice(1, 5, 2)</code> is equivalent to <code>[1:5:2]</code>.</p>",
      "difficulty": "Beginner",
      "tags": ["Python Basics", "Lists", "Slicing"]
