      "question": "What are dictionary comprehensions? Show how to create a dictionary mapping numbers to their squares for even numbers from 1 to 10.",
      "answer": "<p>Dictionary comprehensions create dictionaries from an expression and optional condition.</p>\n<p><b>Syntax:</b> <code>{k: v for item in iterable if condition}</code></p>\n<pre><code># Squares for even numbers only\nsquares = {x: x**2 for x in range(1, 11) if x % 2 == 0}\n# {2: 4, 4: 16, 6: 36, 8: 64, 10: 100}\n\n# Swap keys and values\norig = {'a': 1, 'b': 2}\nswapped = {v: k for k, v in orig.items()}\n# {1: 'a', 2: 'b'}\n\n# Filter by value\nscores = {'alice': 85, 'bob': 42, 'carol': 91}\npassed = {k: v for k, v in scores.items() if v >= 60}\n# {'alice': 85, 'carol': 91}\n\n# Nested dict comprehension\nmatrix = {i: {j: i*j for j in range(3)} for i in range(3)}\n\n# vs dict() with zip for simple pairing\nkeys = ['a', 'b']; vals = [1, 2]\nd1 = dict(zip(keys, vals))  # {'a': 1, 'b': 2}\n</code></pre>\n<p><b>Gotcha:</b> Using mutable values as dict keys in a comprehension will fail — lists and sets are unhashable.</p>",
