      "question": "Explain the difference between <code>is</code> and <code>==</code> in Python. When should each be used?",
      "answer": "<p>They answer completely different questions:</p>\n<ul>\n<li><code>==</code> asks: <b>\"do these objects have equal <i>values</i>?\"</b> — calls <code>obj.__eq__(other)</code>.</li>\n<li><code>is</code> asks: <b>\"are these names pointing at the <i>same object in memory</i>?\"</b> — compares <code>id(obj)</code>.</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Aspect</th><th><code>==</code></th><th><code>is</code></th></tr>\n<tr><td>Question</td><td>Are values equal?</td><td>Is it the same object?</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Mechanism</td><td>Calls <code>__eq__</code></td><td>Compares <code>id()</code></td></tr>\n<tr><td>Overridable</td><td>Yes</td><td>No</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Typical use</td><td>Comparing values</td><td><code>None</code>, sentinels, singletons</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Speed</td><td>Can be slow</td><td>Very fast (pointer compare)</td></tr>\n</table>\n<p><b>Classic gotcha — small ints are interned:</b></p>\n<pre><code>a = 256; b = 256\na is b       # True  (CPython caches -5..256)\n\na = 257; b = 257\na is b       # False (out of cache)\na == b       # True  (values match)\n</code></pre>\n<p><b>Rule of thumb:</b> Use <code>is</code> only for <code>None</code>, <code>True</code>, <code>False</code>, and sentinels. Use <code>==</code> for everything else.</p>\n<pre><code># Correct idioms\nif value is None: ...\n\n# Wrong with collections\n[1, 2, 3] == [1, 2, 3]     # True  — values match\n[1, 2, 3] is [1, 2, 3]     # False — different objects\n\n# Custom __eq__\nclass Money:\n    def __init__(self, amount, currency):\n        self.amount = amount; self.currency = currency\n    def __eq__(self, other):\n        if not isinstance(other, Money): return NotImplemented\n        return self.amount == other.amount and self.currency == other.currency\n    def __hash__(self):\n        return hash((self.amount, self.currency))\n</code></pre>",
