      "question": "Explain Python's <code>*args</code> and <code>**kwargs</code> with examples of how they work in function definitions.",
      "answer": "<p>They allow functions to accept variable numbers of positional and keyword arguments.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b><code>*args</code></b> collects extra positional arguments into a <b>tuple</b>.</li>\n<li><b><code>**kwargs</code></b> collects extra keyword arguments into a <b>dict</b>.</li>\n</ul>\n<pre><code>def demo(a, b, *args, **kwargs):\n    print(f\"a={a}, b={b}\")\n    print(f\"args tuple: {args}\")\n    print(f\"kwargs dict: {kwargs}\")\n\ndemo(1, 2, 3, 4, x=10, y=20)\n# a=1, b=2\n# args tuple: (3, 4)\n# kwargs dict: {'x': 10, 'y': 20}\n\n# Unpacking when calling\ndef add(x, y, z):\n    return x + y + z\n\nnums = [1, 2, 3]\nadd(*nums)          # same as add(1, 2, 3)\n\nparams = {'x': 1, 'y': 2, 'z': 3}\nadd(**params)       # same as add(x=1, y=2, z=3)\n\n# Flexible wrapper\ndef wrapper(*args, **kwargs):\n    print(\"Before\")\n    result = inner(*args, **kwargs)\n    print(\"After\")\n    return result\n\n# Python 3.8+: positional-only and keyword-only\ndef pos_kw(a, /, b, *, c):\n    \"a=positional-only, c=keyword-only, b=either\"\n    pass\n\npos_kw(1, 2, c=3)      # valid\npos_kw(1, b=2, c=3)    # valid\n# pos_kw(a=1, b=2, c=3) # TypeError!\n</code></pre>\n<p><b>Gotcha:</b> <code>*args</code> is a <b>tuple</b> (immutable at top level), but mutable objects inside (like lists) are still shared references.</p>",
      "difficulty": "Beginner",
      "tags": ["Python Basics", "Functions", "Args", "Kwargs"]
