      "question": "What is the difference between deep copy and shallow copy in Python? Demonstrate with nested structures.",
      "answer": "<p>Both create a new outer object, but differ on <b>nested</b> objects.</p>\n<ul>\n<li><b>Shallow copy</b> (<code>copy.copy()</code>, <code>list[:]</code>, <code>dict.copy()</code>): new container, same nested references.</li>\n<li><b>Deep copy</b> (<code>copy.deepcopy()</code>): new container, recursively copies everything — nothing shared.</li>\n</ul>\n<table>\n<tr><th>Aspect</th><th>Shallow copy</th><th>Deep copy</th></tr>\n<tr><td>Top-level changes</td><td>Independent</td><td>Independent</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Nested changes</td><td><b>Affects original!</b></td><td>Independent</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Cost</td><td>Cheap</td><td>Recursive — can be slow</td></tr>\n<tr><td>Use when</td><td>Flat structure, top-level only</td><td>Need full independence</td></tr>\n</table>\n<pre><code>import copy\n\noriginal = [['a', 'b'], ['c', 'd']]\nshallow = copy.copy(original)\ndeep    = copy.deepcopy(original)\n\nshallow[0].append('Z')\nprint(original)   # [['a', 'b', 'Z'], ['c', 'd']] — mutated!\nprint(deep)       # [['a', 'b'],     ['c', 'd']] — untouched\n\n# Slice/constructor copies are also shallow\nmatrix = [[1, 2], [3, 4]]\ncopy_a = matrix[:]\ncopy_a[0][0] = 99\nprint(matrix)     # [[99, 2], [3, 4]] — inner list shared\n</code></pre>\n<p><b>Gotchas:</b></p>\n<ul>\n<li>For flat structures (ints, strings), shallow and deep copy behave identically.</li>\n<li><code>deepcopy</code> tracks already-copied objects, handling reference cycles correctly.</li>\n<li>Custom classes can define <code>__copy__</code> / <code>__deepcopy__</code> to control behavior.</li>\n<li>For nested structures you'll mutate, default to <code>deepcopy</code>.</li>\n</ul>",
      "difficulty": "Intermediate",
      "tags": ["Memory Management", "Copying", "Python"]
